    <p>With the growing power of the printing press (15th century and onwards), and sufficiently large international readers; the mass production and distribution of printed material gave rise to intellectuals and elite as a distinct and independent social class in Europe. The term "literate men" (or "men of letters") is derived from the French term <q lang=fr">homme de lettres</q>, refers to a metaphysical literary society - not synonymous with academic - that became apparent in Europe and America. This long-distance, international, and private correspondence network between the literary figures formed the basis of the concept, <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Republic_of_Letters">Republic of Letters</a></cite> in the 17th century - <cite><a href="http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/611804138">The Printing Press as an Agent of Change</a></cite>, p. 136-138, 1979, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elizabeth_Eisenstein">Elizabeth Eisenstein</a>.</p>

    <p><cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Society">The Royal Society</a></cite> effectively established authority for a metaphyshical community for scientists and scholars. <cite lang="fr"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Journal_des_s%C3%A7avans">Journal des sçavans</a></cite> published in 1665 was the first academic journal in Europe, followed by <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophical_Transactions_of_the_Royal_Society">Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society</a></cite> in the same year.</p>

    <p>The first journal that strongly focused on scientific communication came later in 1666 in <cite lang="fr"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comptes_rendus_de_l%27Acad%C3%A9mie_des_Sciences">Mémoires de l'Académie des Sciences</a></cite></p>
